{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011AMqKXoc92sYSNLhwfXLPm","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tAn ETL pipeline is failing with a memory error in Stage 3.\n2\tYOU must diagnose the root cause and fix the problem.\n3\t\n4\tPROBLEM DESCRIPTION:\n5\t- The ETL pipeline has 3 stages:\n6\t  - Stage 1: Load raw data (events, users, products)\n7\t  - Stage 2: Clean and transform data\n8\t  - Stage 3: Aggregate by user_id  <-- FAILS HERE with a memory error\n9\t- The pipeline keeps failing in Stage 3 with an insufficient-memory error\n10\t  (the JVM heap is far below what Spark needs)\n11\t- Initial investigation shows the job is configured with only 256m of\n12\t  driver/executor memory\n13\t\n14\tYOUR TASK:\n15\t\n16\t1. COLLECT FAILURE INFORMATION\n17\t   - Check the ETL job status and error message\n18\t   - Review driver and executor logs\n19\t   - Look for memory errors (OutOfMemory / \"must be at least ... increase\n20\t     heap size\" messages)\n21\t\n22\t   ```bash\n23\t   # Check ETL job status\n24\t   kubectl get job etl-job -n spark-etl\n25\t\n26\t   # Get job pod logs\n27\t   kubectl logs -n spark-etl -l app=etl-job --tail=100\n28\t\n29\t   # Check for failed pods\n30\t   kubectl get pods -n spark-etl\n31\t   ```\n32\t\n33\t2. DIAGNOSE ROOT CAUSE\n34\t   - Analyze the data distribution\n35\t   - Look for data skew (one user_id has disproportionate records)\n36\t   - Calculate the skew ratio\n37\t\n38\t   ```bash\n39\t   # Check data skew info\n40\t   kubectl exec -n spark-etl -l app=data-generator -- cat /data/skew_info.txt\n41\t\n42\t   # Check diagnostic server logs\n43\t   kubectl logs -n spark-etl -l app=diagnostic-server --tail=50\n44\t   ```\n45\t\n46\t   Expected finding: user_id 999 has ~50% of all records (skew ratio > 10x)\n47\t\n48\t3. FIX THE PROBLEM\n49\t   The job's 256m heap is below what Spark needs, so the required fix is to\n50\t   raise the job's memory:\n51\t   ```bash\n52\t   # Delete failed job\n53\t   kubectl delete job etl-job -n spark-etl\n54\t\n55\t   # Create a new job with increased memory (edit and apply):\n56\t   # raise the 256m memory settings to 1g — both --driver-memory and\n57\t   # spark.executor.memory (in local[2] mode the executor runs inside the\n58\t   # driver JVM) — in etl-job.yaml\n59\t   kubectl apply -f cases/spark/spark_etl_skew_oom/resource/etl-job.yaml\n60\t   ```\n61\t\n62\t   Optionally, for the underlying data skew you may ALSO scale/upsize the\n63\t   workers or enable AQE skew handling on the job:\n64\t   ```bash\n65\t   # Scale workers for more parallelism\n66\t   kubectl scale deployment spark-worker -n spark-etl --replicas=4\n67\t   kubectl set env deployment/spark-worker -n spark-etl SPARK_WORKER_MEMORY=2G\n68\t   kubectl rollout status deployment/spark-worker -n spark-etl\n69\t\n70\t   # And/or add AQE config to the job:\n71\t   # --conf spark.sql.adaptive.enabled=true\n72\t   # --conf spark.sql.adaptive.skewJoin.enabled=true\n73\t   ```\n74\t\n75\t4. RE-RUN THE PIPELINE\n76\t   After applying the fix:\n77\t   ```bash\n78\t   # Re-apply the ETL job\n79\t   kubectl apply -f cases/spark/spark_etl_skew_oom/resource/etl-job.yaml\n80\t\n81\t   # Watch job status\n82\t   kubectl get job etl-job -n spark-etl -w\n83\t   ```\n84\t\n85\t5. VERIFY SUCCESS\n86\t   ```bash\n87\t   # Check job completed\n88\t   kubectl get job etl-job -n spark-etl\n89\t\n90\t   # Check job logs\n91\t   kubectl logs -n spark-etl -l app=etl-job --tail=50\n92\t   ```\n93\t\n94\tSUCCESS CRITERIA:\n95\t- Identified the memory failure in Stage 3\n96\t- Diagnosed data skew (user_id 999 with >10x ratio)\n97\t- Applied a fix (raised the job's memory above 256m; optionally also more\n98\t  workers or AQE)\n99\t- ETL job completed successfully"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3f6f397b-088f-4b90-be30-32220f95c307","uuid":"703c1f4a-a146-4f0c-8127-f8a3724a77b9","timestamp":"2026-07-03T08:20:06.773Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/mydata/karma/runs/short/r7/spark-deep-tuning-20260703_081055/stages/stage_03/prompt.txt","content":"An ETL pipeline is failing with a memory error in Stage 3.\nYOU must diagnose the root cause and fix the problem.\n\nPROBLEM DESCRIPTION:\n- The ETL pipeline has 3 stages:\n  - Stage 1: Load raw data (events, users, products)\n  - Stage 2: Clean and transform data\n  - Stage 3: Aggregate by user_id  <-- FAILS HERE with a memory error\n- The pipeline keeps failing in Stage 3 with an insufficient-memory error\n  (the JVM heap is far below what Spark needs)\n- Initial investigation shows the job is configured with only 256m of\n  driver/executor memory\n\nYOUR TASK:\n\n1. COLLECT FAILURE INFORMATION\n   - Check the ETL job status and error message\n   - Review driver and executor logs\n   - Look for memory errors (OutOfMemory / \"must be at least ... increase\n     heap size\" messages)\n\n   ```bash\n   # Check ETL job status\n   kubectl get job etl-job -n spark-etl\n\n   # Get job pod logs\n   kubectl logs -n spark-etl -l app=etl-job --tail=100\n\n   # Check for failed pods\n   kubectl get pods -n spark-etl\n   ```\n\n2. DIAGNOSE ROOT CAUSE\n   - Analyze the data distribution\n   - Look for data skew (one user_id has disproportionate records)\n   - Calculate the skew ratio\n\n   ```bash\n   # Check data skew info\n   kubectl exec -n spark-etl -l app=data-generator -- cat /data/skew_info.txt\n\n   # Check diagnostic server logs\n   kubectl logs -n spark-etl -l app=diagnostic-server --tail=50\n   ```\n\n   Expected finding: user_id 999 has ~50% of all records (skew ratio > 10x)\n\n3. FIX THE PROBLEM\n   The job's 256m heap is below what Spark needs, so the required fix is to\n   raise the job's memory:\n   ```bash\n   # Delete failed job\n   kubectl delete job etl-job -n spark-etl\n\n   # Create a new job with increased memory (edit and apply):\n   # raise the 256m memory settings to 1g — both --driver-memory and\n   # spark.executor.memory (in local[2] mode the executor runs inside the\n   # driver JVM) — in etl-job.yaml\n   kubectl apply -f cases/spark/spark_etl_skew_oom/resource/etl-job.yaml\n   ```\n\n   Optionally, for the underlying data skew you may ALSO scale/upsize the\n   workers or enable AQE skew handling on the job:\n   ```bash\n   # Scale workers for more parallelism\n   kubectl scale deployment spark-worker -n spark-etl --replicas=4\n   kubectl set env deployment/spark-worker -n spark-etl SPARK_WORKER_MEMORY=2G\n   kubectl rollout status deployment/spark-worker -n spark-etl\n\n   # And/or add AQE config to the job:\n   # --conf spark.sql.adaptive.enabled=true\n   # --conf spark.sql.adaptive.skewJoin.enabled=true\n   ```\n\n4. RE-RUN THE PIPELINE\n   After applying the fix:\n   ```bash\n   # Re-apply the ETL job\n   kubectl apply -f cases/spark/spark_etl_skew_oom/resource/etl-job.yaml\n\n   # Watch job status\n   kubectl get job etl-job -n spark-etl -w\n   ```\n\n5. VERIFY SUCCESS\n   ```bash\n   # Check job completed\n   kubectl get job etl-job -n spark-etl\n\n   # Check job logs\n   kubectl logs -n spark-etl -l app=etl-job --tail=50\n   ```\n\nSUCCESS CRITERIA:\n- Identified the memory failure in Stage 3\n- Diagnosed data skew (user_id 999 with >10x ratio)\n- Applied a fix (raised the job's memory above 256m; optionally also more\n  workers or AQE)\n- ETL job completed successfully","numLines":99,"startLine":1,"totalLines":99}}}
